<tt>Tue Nov 26  8:25:06 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
My name is Teresa and I have been a supporter and activist for POW-MIA and veterans
issues for @8 years now.  I am not a veteran, but hold those who are very close to my
heart.  I am very grateful to all of you for all of your tremendous sacrifics and am
now currently working towards a degree in Social Work so that i might be of better
help to you!  <br><br>
Anyway, I am heart sick when I think of all those left behind, and for the families
that just don't know for sure what happened to their loved ones.  You must think
about it -- sure -- it's been 20+ years so &quot;they must all be dead by now!!&quot; 
WHY must they??? There will always be a doubt, won't there??? A mother can not mourn
for her dead son if she does not know for sure he is dead . . . We must always keep
faith and never give up on our men and women until we have knowingly done everything
humanly possible to try and find them or what has happened to them!<br><br>
For a quick example, take Lt. Col. David L. Hrdlicka.  He is the main man I have
adopted as mine and I have been wearing his bracelet since 1988 and have been very
loyal and faithful to him.  He went down on May 18, 1965.  There was a picture of him
in a Russian paper as a POW. In 1973, when we had our homecoming, why did we not ask,
&quot;Hey, what about David???&quot; Why did we not say that &quot;You had him last
-- here is a photo -- is that not you -- is that not Dave??? If he died, fine -- show
me his burial place -- show me his remains?&quot;  Why??? Because we were never
&quot;in Laos&quot; so how could we ask for him??? Therefore, it is better to just
write him off as another casuality!!  <br><br>
Sorry for going off on my soap box -- I get so mad about this issue!! Anyway, thanks
for being there for me and my family!  I love all you guys and gals -- and <br><br>
                 WELCOME HOME!!!!!!<br><br>
